1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:02,580
Meet the most famous
watch dealer on the planet,

2
00:00:02,580 --> 00:00:03,810
Nico Leonard.

3
00:00:03,810 --> 00:00:06,240
He's best known for
roasting celeb watches,

4
00:00:06,240 --> 00:00:08,790
selling multi-million dollar time pieces,

5
00:00:08,790 --> 00:00:11,820
and being the most
subscribed watch expert ever.

6
00:00:11,820 --> 00:00:13,680
But, it wasn't always this way.

7
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:16,620
Today, I want to understand
what makes Nico tick.

8
00:00:16,620 --> 00:00:18,960
This means diving into his background,

9
00:00:18,960 --> 00:00:23,010
his businesses, and his
deepest insecurities.

10
00:00:23,010 --> 00:00:25,800
This is a story you don't
want to miss a second of,

11
00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:28,536
as you've never seen him
open up like this before.

12
00:00:28,536 --> 00:00:30,987
- [Nico] This is something
I haven't digged in.

13
00:00:31,990 --> 00:00:33,073
- [Mark] Mmm.

14
00:00:34,760 --> 00:00:36,900
- In many years, if you
know what I mean, so.

15
00:00:36,900 --> 00:00:39,600
- [Mark] So let's wind
his rags to riches story

16
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:41,640
back to the beginning.

17
00:00:41,640 --> 00:00:44,850
Now as I understand it, you
were brought up in Amsterdam

18
00:00:44,850 --> 00:00:46,140
and you moved to Ireland.

19
00:00:46,140 --> 00:00:48,750
So, what initiated that big move?

20
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:49,950
- A change in life.

21
00:00:49,950 --> 00:00:52,950
I needed a change in life, desperately.

22
00:00:52,950 --> 00:00:57,840
Being unhappy, being lost,
just a change of scenery,

23
00:00:57,840 --> 00:00:59,400
change of friends.

24
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:01,230
I wasn't rolling in the right circles,

25
00:01:01,230 --> 00:01:03,703
and I wanted to achieve
something in my life.

26
00:01:03,703 --> 00:01:07,230
I just wanted to be
happy and, and I wasn't.

27
00:01:07,230 --> 00:01:08,460
- So what was the dream?

28
00:01:08,460 --> 00:01:11,310
- I had the opportunity to prove myself

29
00:01:11,310 --> 00:01:13,980
in Northern Ireland playing football.

30
00:01:13,980 --> 00:01:15,030
I moved to Northern Ireland,

31
00:01:15,030 --> 00:01:18,300
packed everything I
had, but unfortunately,

32
00:01:18,300 --> 00:01:21,120
I broke my ankle in
literally my first month.

33
00:01:21,120 --> 00:01:23,250
- So your dreams came
shattering down there.

34
00:01:23,250 --> 00:01:24,990
So how did that feel mentally, I mean,

35
00:01:24,990 --> 00:01:27,690
that puts a big void in your life.

36
00:01:27,690 --> 00:01:29,220
- I was devastated.

37
00:01:29,220 --> 00:01:31,350
Achieving, becoming a footballer, though,

38
00:01:31,350 --> 00:01:33,360
that was my main goal. It was all I knew.

39
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:36,120
I wasn't doing well at school,
I don't have any diplomas.

40
00:01:36,120 --> 00:01:37,230
That's all I wanted to do.

41
00:01:37,230 --> 00:01:40,110
And that's all I did when I was younger.

42
00:01:40,110 --> 00:01:42,540
I didn't achieve it.
I let my parents down.

43
00:01:42,540 --> 00:01:45,030
And I've lived with that
for many years after.

44
00:01:45,030 --> 00:01:47,253
My parents gave up everything for me,

45
00:01:48,232 --> 00:01:52,500
to clear the road so I can play football,

46
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:55,980
and I can maybe even make it a job.

47
00:01:55,980 --> 00:01:59,040
I remember my first
surgery on my left knee.

48
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:01,590
It was just a simple surgery,
you called a meniscus surgery.

49
00:02:01,590 --> 00:02:03,810
You drill three holes to do a camera,

50
00:02:03,810 --> 00:02:07,890
and fix whatever they fix, and over with.

51
00:02:07,890 --> 00:02:09,540
We all thought that was it.

52
00:02:09,540 --> 00:02:12,847
But all of a sudden, listen,
"The first surgery...

53
00:02:12,847 --> 00:02:15,657
"we found the problem,
and we couldn't fix it."

54
00:02:17,010 --> 00:02:21,840
And it's like, "Oh, okay,
talk to me, how do we fix it?"

55
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:25,387
They're like, "We'll have to
reconstruct your entire knee,

56
00:02:25,387 --> 00:02:26,220
"and this and that."

57
00:02:26,220 --> 00:02:27,607
And it's like, "But like,
what does that mean?

58
00:02:27,607 --> 00:02:28,589
"What does that mean?"

59
00:02:28,589 --> 00:02:32,790
It meant that I had, like, 5 or 10% chance

60
00:02:32,790 --> 00:02:33,810
to play football again.

61
00:02:33,810 --> 00:02:36,360
That's the first time I've
ever seen my father cry.

62
00:02:36,360 --> 00:02:39,300
That was rough. That
was rough at that time.

63
00:02:39,300 --> 00:02:43,743
I have never experienced pain
in my life like it. Right?

64
00:02:44,640 --> 00:02:48,660
If you're ever in a moment
of absolute desperation,

65
00:02:48,660 --> 00:02:51,877
ask yourself this question,
"God, if you exist,

66
00:02:51,877 --> 00:02:54,807
"show yourself, because
now I need you the most."

67
00:02:55,950 --> 00:02:59,853
Fuck; don't put that shit
on camera, please, but.

68
00:03:03,129 --> 00:03:04,530
Fuck you.
(both laugh)

69
00:03:04,530 --> 00:03:07,950
- But the thing is, at
17 you're not equipped

70
00:03:07,950 --> 00:03:09,607
to be able to deal with
these emotions, are you?

71
00:03:09,607 --> 00:03:11,400
- No
- That's the trouble.

72
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:13,863
- This is something I haven't digged in

73
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:20,250
in many years, if you
know what I mean, so, wow.

74
00:03:23,640 --> 00:03:25,620
I don't know if I told myself this.

75
00:03:25,620 --> 00:03:27,270
I don't know if I fell asleep.

76
00:03:27,270 --> 00:03:29,820
I don't know, whatever it is,

77
00:03:29,820 --> 00:03:32,610
because I always tried to
look at things very rational,

78
00:03:32,610 --> 00:03:34,260
black and white.

79
00:03:34,260 --> 00:03:37,083
But damn right I had a
period where I had no pain.

80
00:03:37,980 --> 00:03:40,719
Hell to break me in
that way, like, fuck me.

81
00:03:40,719 --> 00:03:41,552
(rhythmic music)

82
00:03:41,552 --> 00:03:42,923
- Can you see the ball, or what?

83
00:03:42,923 --> 00:03:43,756
- Yeah, come on.

84
00:03:43,756 --> 00:03:45,310
(sound of foot kicking ball)

85
00:03:45,310 --> 00:03:48,003
- Ball's in net.
(both cheer)

86
00:03:48,003 --> 00:03:48,836
(inaudible conversation)

87
00:03:48,836 --> 00:03:50,002
(rhythmic music continues)

88
00:03:50,002 --> 00:03:52,548
(inaudible comments)

89
00:03:52,548 --> 00:03:53,769
(sound of foot kicking ball)

90
00:03:53,769 --> 00:03:54,602
(sound of foot kicking ball)

91
00:03:54,602 --> 00:03:56,430
- Price & Pinion and the
watch business as it is today,

92
00:03:56,430 --> 00:03:59,190
is the first time I
actually succeeded in life.

93
00:03:59,190 --> 00:04:00,750
After everything I've done,

94
00:04:00,750 --> 00:04:04,200
I didn't do well at school,
in anything I've ever done,

95
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:07,650
In every job I've ever had, I got fired.

96
00:04:07,650 --> 00:04:09,240
- Do you have a problem with authority?

97
00:04:09,240 --> 00:04:11,970
- Yes. Significantly. Yeah. Yeah.

98
00:04:11,970 --> 00:04:13,440
And I'm always late, as well.

99
00:04:13,440 --> 00:04:15,060
- Yeah. I mean, I have a similar problem

100
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:16,530
with being bossed around at work,

101
00:04:16,530 --> 00:04:19,620
and I think we resigned in a similar way.

102
00:04:19,620 --> 00:04:21,307
I mean, I literally had enough and I went,

103
00:04:21,307 --> 00:04:24,240
"That's it, I'm going.
There's my notice I'm off."

104
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:25,920
And I think you had a similar situation.

105
00:04:25,920 --> 00:04:28,200
- I remember me driving into the office,

106
00:04:28,200 --> 00:04:29,580
and you need to go into the basement,

107
00:04:29,580 --> 00:04:31,260
because the parking, you park up.

108
00:04:31,260 --> 00:04:33,660
And I remember opening the door,

109
00:04:33,660 --> 00:04:35,040
and I stepped outta the car,

110
00:04:35,040 --> 00:04:36,213
and I knew it when I looked around,

111
00:04:36,213 --> 00:04:39,780
that this was gonna be the
last time I was gonna be here.

112
00:04:39,780 --> 00:04:40,710
It's really weird.

113
00:04:40,710 --> 00:04:42,150
And I resigned there and then.

114
00:04:42,150 --> 00:04:45,105
within 15 minutes I
jumped back in the car.

115
00:04:45,105 --> 00:04:48,675
(rhythmic music)

116
00:04:48,675 --> 00:04:49,508
- At this door, here, guys, look at it,

117
00:04:51,660 --> 00:04:53,537
it's a solid door.

118
00:04:53,537 --> 00:04:54,731
- [Nico] {indistinct} for tomorrow.

119
00:04:54,731 --> 00:04:55,564
- Can't even move it.

120
00:04:55,564 --> 00:04:56,397
Wow.

121
00:04:56,397 --> 00:04:58,590
- So what you see here
is basically everything

122
00:04:58,590 --> 00:05:02,130
from about a thousand pounds
upwards to a half a mil

123
00:05:02,130 --> 00:05:04,020
to even further than that.

124
00:05:04,020 --> 00:05:05,790
From extremely rare vintage

125
00:05:05,790 --> 00:05:09,180
to really, really cool quirky watches.

126
00:05:09,180 --> 00:05:12,690
Everything you see is watches
that I really, really love.

127
00:05:12,690 --> 00:05:15,600
And that's what I want to
display, watches that I love,

128
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:16,830
that's the watches I wanna sell.

129
00:05:16,830 --> 00:05:19,560
That's why I don't sell certain brands.

130
00:05:19,560 --> 00:05:21,210
I refuse to sell certain brands,

131
00:05:21,210 --> 00:05:22,680
because I just don't like them.

132
00:05:22,680 --> 00:05:25,036
Yeah. It's passion above profit.
That's how I approach it.

133
00:05:25,036 --> 00:05:26,550
(theme music)

134
00:05:26,550 --> 00:05:29,400
- So you didn't have a job,
you didn't have any plans.

135
00:05:29,400 --> 00:05:30,960
What was your first move?

136
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:33,630
- Funny enough, in any of
my companies that I have,

137
00:05:33,630 --> 00:05:35,550
I've never written a business plan.

138
00:05:35,550 --> 00:05:39,000
I just knew, I just wanted
to go into the watch world.

139
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:40,980
I always, I'm obsessed with watches,

140
00:05:40,980 --> 00:05:44,010
and I fixed and repaired
watches as a side hustle,

141
00:05:44,010 --> 00:05:45,480
making a few quid.

142
00:05:45,480 --> 00:05:49,140
But, how do you make money with watches?

143
00:05:49,140 --> 00:05:51,630
And that's literally,
literally where I looked at.

144
00:05:51,630 --> 00:05:55,200
I can either go ahead with
repairing and fixing watches,

145
00:05:55,200 --> 00:05:56,700
but I'm not making really good money,

146
00:05:56,700 --> 00:06:00,000
not good enough to maintain myself.

147
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:01,650
Let's try sellin' then.

148
00:06:01,650 --> 00:06:04,950
- So what was the first
watch you bought and sold?

149
00:06:04,950 --> 00:06:07,950
- Tudor Pelagos, Breitling Navitimer,

150
00:06:07,950 --> 00:06:11,340
and a Rolex Datejust,
reference number 1 1 6 2 3 4.

151
00:06:11,340 --> 00:06:12,270
Black dial.

152
00:06:12,270 --> 00:06:13,380
- So straight in.

153
00:06:13,380 --> 00:06:14,310
- Straight in no kissing.

154
00:06:14,310 --> 00:06:15,210
- No plan B.

155
00:06:15,210 --> 00:06:17,730
- If you give yourself
the slightest possibility

156
00:06:17,730 --> 00:06:20,940
that you have a safety
net, or there's an exit,

157
00:06:20,940 --> 00:06:24,090
then you'll never, ever push
yourself to the limit. Never.

158
00:06:24,090 --> 00:06:27,150
- Well, selling one or
two watches is one thing,

159
00:06:27,150 --> 00:06:29,943
but scaling that, how
did you bridge the gap?

160
00:06:32,160 --> 00:06:35,313
- I got a lot of help, a
lot of incredible people.

161
00:06:36,300 --> 00:06:38,550
I'm a foreigner in a
country that isn't mine

162
00:06:38,550 --> 00:06:40,890
selling watches in the boot of my car.

163
00:06:40,890 --> 00:06:41,723
I mean,

164
00:06:41,723 --> 00:06:42,556
- That's mad, isn't it?

165
00:06:42,556 --> 00:06:43,650
- That's fuckin' mad.

166
00:06:43,650 --> 00:06:47,220
I don't get why people actually
trusted me at the time.

167
00:06:47,220 --> 00:06:48,510
I wouldn't have.

168
00:06:48,510 --> 00:06:50,850
Like, a guy that no one knows who are you.

169
00:06:50,850 --> 00:06:53,340
I could have easily
swapped it for a fake one.

170
00:06:53,340 --> 00:06:54,390
That's not me.

171
00:06:54,390 --> 00:06:56,610
In my small way, I wanted
to make a small impact

172
00:06:56,610 --> 00:06:58,410
on the watch industry.

173
00:06:58,410 --> 00:07:00,480
- So how does it feel
to have this vault here

174
00:07:00,480 --> 00:07:02,970
with this massive
collection of watches in it?

175
00:07:02,970 --> 00:07:04,530
- It is a really, really special feeling.

176
00:07:04,530 --> 00:07:06,330
I'm not very often in the shop anymore

177
00:07:06,330 --> 00:07:07,500
but to give you an idea,

178
00:07:07,500 --> 00:07:10,380
when I started my business and
when I got the shop fitted,

179
00:07:10,380 --> 00:07:13,500
and it cost me about 26 or 25,000 pounds

180
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:14,880
to fit the store up,

181
00:07:14,880 --> 00:07:16,940
and that was the last
money I had at the time.

182
00:07:16,940 --> 00:07:18,540
I didn't really have any watches,

183
00:07:18,540 --> 00:07:21,180
because I had to sell
everything to build the shop.

184
00:07:21,180 --> 00:07:23,970
I sat here on that chair
for two and a half years,

185
00:07:23,970 --> 00:07:26,880
every single day, at eight
o'clock sharp til six o'clock,

186
00:07:26,880 --> 00:07:29,430
every single day, including a Sunday,

187
00:07:29,430 --> 00:07:31,020
to just try to sell some watches.

188
00:07:31,020 --> 00:07:33,300
And the funny bit is, I didn't
even have a card machine.

189
00:07:33,300 --> 00:07:36,270
I've sat on that chair for two
and a half years every day,

190
00:07:36,270 --> 00:07:38,910
no daylight, nothing.

191
00:07:38,910 --> 00:07:41,550
Just to build the business
to where it is now.

192
00:07:41,550 --> 00:07:42,856
It's unbelievable, aye?

193
00:07:42,856 --> 00:07:43,689
- It's great, isn't it?

194
00:07:43,689 --> 00:07:44,522
- Ah.

195
00:07:44,522 --> 00:07:47,130
- So what's the most expensive
watch you've ever sold?

196
00:07:47,130 --> 00:07:49,770
Because that's gotta put
you on such a high, as well.

197
00:07:49,770 --> 00:07:50,820
- The most expensive watch

198
00:07:50,820 --> 00:07:52,740
that my team and myself have ever sold

199
00:07:52,740 --> 00:07:55,230
was 7 million US dollars.

200
00:07:55,230 --> 00:07:57,030
- 7 million dollars.

201
00:07:57,030 --> 00:07:59,190
So was that one lump sum?

202
00:07:59,190 --> 00:08:01,740
Here's a watch, here's $7 million.

203
00:08:01,740 --> 00:08:02,760
- No, it was different.

204
00:08:02,760 --> 00:08:05,220
It was, "Here's the money,
here you have the watch."

205
00:08:05,220 --> 00:08:06,390
- In reverse?

206
00:08:06,390 --> 00:08:08,490
So you always mention your
team, and you are very

207
00:08:08,490 --> 00:08:09,900
respectful of those.
- Yeah.

208
00:08:09,900 --> 00:08:11,880
- Why couldn't you have
made it on your own?

209
00:08:11,880 --> 00:08:12,750
- You're only as good

210
00:08:12,750 --> 00:08:14,730
as the people you have around you, right?

211
00:08:14,730 --> 00:08:18,990
And I have incredible
people around me, right?

212
00:08:18,990 --> 00:08:22,573
And genuinely, to scale a business,

213
00:08:27,780 --> 00:08:30,300
no one can ever scale a business alone.

214
00:08:30,300 --> 00:08:31,680
It's impossible.

215
00:08:31,680 --> 00:08:33,600
You can have an idea,
you can have visionary,

216
00:08:33,600 --> 00:08:35,490
you're not a superhuman, right?

217
00:08:35,490 --> 00:08:37,800
I am not very good in organizing things.

218
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:40,350
I am most probably the most
chaotic person on the planet.

219
00:08:40,350 --> 00:08:42,990
But if I commit to something, I do it,

220
00:08:42,990 --> 00:08:44,820
and I will finish that job.

221
00:08:44,820 --> 00:08:47,310
Why I wouldn't be able to do
it without my team is because

222
00:08:47,310 --> 00:08:48,990
everyone has his qualities.

223
00:08:48,990 --> 00:08:50,970
- Well, I think the mark
of a good businessman

224
00:08:50,970 --> 00:08:53,580
is to recognize someone
that can do something

225
00:08:53,580 --> 00:08:54,870
better than yourself.
- [Nico] Oh.

226
00:08:54,870 --> 00:08:57,000
- And as soon as you get to that stage,

227
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:59,220
you keep recognizing
parts of your business

228
00:08:59,220 --> 00:09:01,080
that can be done better by someone else.

229
00:09:01,080 --> 00:09:02,073
- Yeah, exactly.

230
00:09:02,916 --> 00:09:04,470
Hi. Hello.
(staff/Mark greet each other)

231
00:09:04,470 --> 00:09:06,033
- [Nico] Stephanie, meet Mark.

232
00:09:06,033 --> 00:09:07,012
- [Stephanie] Hello.

233
00:09:07,012 --> 00:09:08,727
- [Nico] Ashley, meet Mark.
- [Mark] Hey Stephanie.

234
00:09:08,727 --> 00:09:09,785
- [Stephanie] Nice to meet you.

235
00:09:09,785 --> 00:09:10,921
- [Mark] Ashley, did you say, yes?

236
00:09:10,921 --> 00:09:11,754
- [Ashley] Yes, hi.

237
00:09:11,754 --> 00:09:13,320
- [Nico] This is where the magic happens.

238
00:09:13,320 --> 00:09:16,830
Admin, office, my personal aide,

239
00:09:16,830 --> 00:09:18,840
and all sorts of things
are being arranged here.

240
00:09:18,840 --> 00:09:20,596
- I mean, that's a job,
isn't it, organizing him?

241
00:09:20,596 --> 00:09:21,930
(Stephanie laughs and
makes inaudible remark)

242
00:09:21,930 --> 00:09:23,100
- [Nico] That's a nightmare.

243
00:09:23,100 --> 00:09:24,633
- I love the mural on the wall.

244
00:09:24,633 --> 00:09:25,482
- [Nico] Brilliant, isn't it?

245
00:09:25,482 --> 00:09:27,090
So, this is the Amsterdam Marina.

246
00:09:27,090 --> 00:09:27,960
This is a surprise.

247
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:32,490
This was Steven's surprise
whenever we moved in.

248
00:09:32,490 --> 00:09:34,020
A bit of home.

249
00:09:34,020 --> 00:09:36,180
It's a bit of home, and a
pitch I was supposed to play.

250
00:09:36,180 --> 00:09:37,320
- [Mark] More magic.

251
